1 (l) The Office of the State Auditor is exempt from this Part and may procure information
2 technology services pursuant to G.S. 147-64.7(b)(1)."
3 SECTION 4. G.S. 147-64.4 reads as rewritten:
4 "§ 147-64.4. Definitions.
5 The following definitions apply in this Article:
6 …
7 (5) Publicly funded entity. – Any individual, private corporation, institution,
8 association, board, or other organization that receives, disburses, or otherwise
9 handles State or federal funds."
10 SECTION 5. G.S. 147-64.6B(b) reads as rewritten:
11 "(b) The Auditor shall investigate reports of allegations of improper governmental
12 activities of State agencies and State employees agencies, employees of those agencies, and
13 publicly funded entities within the scope of authority set forth in G.S. 147-64.6, including
14 misappropriation, mismanagement, or waste of State resources, fraud, violations of State or
15 federal law, rule or regulation by State agencies or State employees administering State or federal
16 programs, and substantial and specific danger to the public health and safety. When the allegation
17 involves issues of substantial and specific danger to the public health and safety, the Auditor
18 shall notify the appropriate State agency immediately. When the Auditor believes that an
19 allegation of improper governmental activity is outside the authority set forth in G.S. 147-64.6,
20 the Auditor shall refer the allegation to the appropriate State agency responsible for the
21 enforcement or administration of the matter for investigation. When the Auditor believes that an
22 allegation of improper governmental activity involves matters set forth in subdivisions (1), (2),
23 or (3) of this subsection, those matters shall be referred as follows:
24 (1) Allegations of criminal misconduct to either the State Bureau of Investigation
25 or the District Attorney for the county where the alleged misconduct occurred.
26 (2) Allegations of violations of Chapter 138A, Chapter 120C and Article 14 of
27 Chapter 120 of the General Statutes to the State Ethics Commission.
28 (3) Allegations of violations of Chapter 163 of the General Statutes to the State
29 Board of Elections."
30 SECTION 6. G.S. 147-64.7 reads as rewritten:
31 "§ 147-64.7. Authority.
32 (a) Access to Persons and Records. –
33 (1) The Auditor and the Auditor's authorized representatives shall have ready
34 access to persons and may examine and copy all books, records, reports,
35 vouchers, correspondence, files, personnel files, investments, and any other
36 documentation of any State agency. Upon demand of the Auditor, access shall
37 extend to continuous and unrestricted view of databases, datasets, and digital
38 records necessary for any purpose within the authority of the Auditor,
39 including performing audits of any type, assessing government efficiency, risk
40 assessment, fraud detection, audit planning, and evidence gathering. The
41 review of State tax returns shall be limited to matters of official business and
42 the Auditor's report shall not violate the confidentiality provisions of tax laws.
43 Notwithstanding confidentiality provisions of tax laws, the Auditor may use
44 and disclose information related to overdue tax debts in support of the
45 Auditor's statutory mission.
46 (2) The For audits or investigations conducted under G.S. 147-64.6(c)(25), the
47 Auditor and the Auditor's duly authorized representatives shall have such
48 access to persons, records, papers, reports, vouchers, correspondence, books,
49 databases, datasets, digital records, and any other documentation which that
50 is in the possession of any individual, private corporation, institution,
